statement:
\emph{Determine whether each statement is true. If it is, explain why;
if not, give a counter-example.}

Given polynomials $f(x)$ and \emph{g}(\emph{x}),

\begin{align*}\lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\end{align*} is equal to 0, $\infty$ or
$-\infty$.

sols:
The statement is false. Let's take polynomials that not only have a
nonzero horizontal asymptote but that also always obtain their
asymptote! We can choose constant functions for \emph{f} and \emph{g}
(these are polynomials!) So suppose that
$\displaystyle f(x) = g(x) = 1$. Then, the limit becomes

\begin{align*}\displaystyle \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{1}{1} = 1\end{align*}

which is not \emph{0} and does not diverge to $\pm \infty$.

\emph{Note:} If, for some reason, you don't like constant polynomials
there is a whole zoo of non-constant polynomials \emph{f} and \emph{g}
with quotients approaching any horizontal asymptote you want, e.g.

\begin{align*}\displaystyle \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{17x+1}{x} = 17.\end{align*}
